<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC"><gtr:id>63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC</gtr:id><gtr:name>John Innes Centre</gtr:name><gtr:department>Contracts Office</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Norwich Research Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Colney</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Norwich</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NR4 7UH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC"><gtr:id>63A7C928-3A19-4C14-812F-370961534DAC</gtr:id><gtr:name>John Innes Centre</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Norwich Research Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Colney</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Norwich</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NR4 7UH</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/F2DDB4A0-400A-4441-88F3-5C9389AF6784"><gtr:id>F2DDB4A0-400A-4441-88F3-5C9389AF6784</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Caroline</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Dean</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=BBS%2FE%2FJ%2F000CA344"><gtr:id>DF4BB040-6EA3-4285-9B8F-CD63E15FFBE3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Molecular analysis of the natural variation in vernalization response of Arabidopsis accessions</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>BBS/E/J/000CA344</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The model plant A. thaliana shows a wide range of genetic and phenotypic variation among natural accessions. Notably, adaptation of flowering time to specific environmental conditions is essential for reproductive success. This proposal will use our knowledge of the molecular basis of vernalization to uncover how Arabidopsis thaliana accessions have adapted to their environment. Analysis of flowering time and vernalization in Arabidopsis accessions provides a unique opportunity to link mechanistic understanding of a complex trait with an understanding of the fitness consequences of different alleles and their distribution within the population. The specific aims of this project will be 1) to fully define the molecular variation at FLC and linked genes underpinning the natural variation in accessions selected to represent a wide range of vernalization responses and 2) use the different accessions as a pool of 'natural mutants' to gain a better understanding of the basis of FLC regulation during vernalization. We will first confirm that FLC cis-elements are involved in this variation by a complementation analysis, followed by mix and match experiments to determine which region contains the cis-regulatory elements that account for the variation. We will also analyse the epigenetic changes at the FLC locus which result from the polymorphisms in the ciselements, as well as the role of other chromosome 5 candidates identified in a QTL analysis for the variation in vernalization response. In parallel, we will characterize important cis-elements in FLC required to initiate and maintain FLC repression during and after vernalization. We will then pick natural variants with polymorphisms in these cis-elements. Dissecting the molecular basis of adaptation is a major goal in evolutionary genetics and the results from this study are likely to provide important insights into adaptation relevant to many biological systems.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-03-16</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-03-17</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_PROJECTED</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>121511</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Dr Vincent Coustham received comprehensive training in genetics, chromatin biochemistry and epigenetics. He continued on a BBSRC grant after this Marie Curie Fellowship finished. He then won an INRA post-doctoral fellowship in Versailles in plant biology and soon after a permanent position at INRA Tour working on epigenetics in chickens. His work resulted in a first author paper in Science on his work. This work had a significant influence on the thinking of evolutionary biologists about the mechanism of adaptive change.</gtr:description><gtr:id>0459E56C-E161-46B1-9C64-B23AF2733B10</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5458e30bb840e7.06469966</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The main finding of the fellowship was that non-coding polymorphisms within a floral repressor gene contribute to adaptation by altering a conserved chromatin silencing mechanism. Arabidopsis thaliana accessions have adapted to growth in a wide range of climates. Variation in flowering and alignment of vernalization response with winter length are central to this adaptation. Vernalization involves the epigenetic silencing of the A. thaliana floral repressor FLC by prolonged cold via a conserved Polycomb (PRC2) mechanism involving histone methylation (H3K27me3). Dr Coustham analysed an A. thaliana accession from the northern extreme of its range and show that variation for response to winter length maps to non-coding cis polymorphism within FLC. A rare combination of up to five polymorphisms, which localise to the nucleation region of a PHD-Polycomb complex, determined the need for longer cold. Chromatin immunoprecipitation experiments and numerical simulations indicated that multiple aspects of the Polycomb silencing process may be attenuated by these polymorphisms, including both initial levels and the cold-induced accumulation of H3K27me3. 

The most important and generic finding relevant to all biology is that quantitative modulation of chromatin silencing through cis variation may be a general mechanism contributing to rapid evolutionary change.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>These data and concepts are significantly influencing thinking in the evolutionary field.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>7A7CDEE9-06D7-4BD6-AC0E-8AD4CEA82C56</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-6369888322.772355779f7f6a</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.jic.ac.uk/staff/caroline-dean/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E358F97F-F51C-46F0-A8E0-9E21B9B1490F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Multiple FLC haplotypes defined by independent cis-regulatory variation underpin life history diversity in Arabidopsis thaliana.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Genes &amp; development</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/46346cbf44e848fbe06e531688e1a872"><gtr:id>46346cbf44e848fbe06e531688e1a872</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Li P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0890-9369</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>543fc1a6e0a8c2.74118329</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>7E23A0FB-DA2E-4181-B982-FFA2379FA845</gtr:id><gtr:title>Quantitative modulation of polycomb silencing underlies natural variation in vernalization.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Science (New York, N.Y.)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8b415529d76eaafd5f92c4712a918058"><gtr:id>8b415529d76eaafd5f92c4712a918058</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Coustham V</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></